CentralDB development (work-in-progress)

Hao Zhang

27 June 2017

This document is served as a log for the development of the centralized database (“CentralDB”) for the H&H modeling team at the Philadelphia Water Department.

Goal

  • Create a database that integrates several data sources:

    • NOAA-monitored meteorological data (Daily, Hourly, HPCP, ASOS)
    • NOAA-monitored tide data
    • PWD-monitored precipitation data
    • Temporary flow monitoring data
    • Outlying-community flow monitoring data
    • WPCP flow monitoring data

  • Develop a workflow for managing the database:

    • automatic download noaa data through NOAA API
    • automatic process noaa data to conform to existing table structure
    • automatic QAQC noaa data
    • automatic append noaa data
    • import PWD rain data
    • import WPCP data
    • store documentations (URL)
    • log changes
    • generate data inventory
    • perform analysis

  • Develop a front-end:

    • build in shiny app ( resemble pilotDB)
    • include pre-designed plots
    • downloadable data

Database Structure

Schema

  • public: includes all tables and views

  • (?) custom: NOAA, PWD, flow_monitoring

Tables

  • QCLCD_HOURLY : hourly meteorological data from QCLCD dataset
    • daily_QCLCD: 50 columns, 2007 May to Present
    • daily_QCLCD_pre2007May : 24 columns, 1996 July - 2007 May
    • hourly_QCLCD: 44 columns, 2007 May to Present
    • hourly_QCLCD_pre2007May: 21 columns, 1996 July - 2007 May
    • hourly_precip_QCLCD : 5 columns, 2007 May to Present
    • hourly_precip_QCLCD_pre2007May: 4 columns, 1996 July - 2007 May
    • hourly_remarks_QCLCD: 4 columns, 2007 May to Present
  • GHCN_DAILY : daily meteorological data from GHCND dataset
    • daily_GHCND: 26 columns, 6 indices (prcp, tmax, tmin, tavg, snwd, snow), each with 1 value + 3 flags, 1948 to present
  • HPCP : hourly precipitation from COOP:HPCP dataset
    • hourly_precip_HPCP: 4 columns, precipitation only, 1900 to 2013 (dry periods omitted)
  • TIDE : tide observation for multiple station
    • 6min_tide: 8 columns, 6min tide data with 4 flags, 4 NOAA stations (Phila, Bridesburg, Tacony, Burlington), entire monitoring period
    • hourly_tide: 7 columns, hourly tide data with 3 flags, 5 NOAA stations (Pier11, Phila, Bridesburg, Tacony, Burlington), entire monitoring period
    • 6min_tide_pred: 2 columns, 6min tide prediction for NOAA Philadelphia station, 2010 to one year in future (2018)

  • PWD: 2.5min precipitation data for 35 PWD rain gauges

    • rain_tips_allrg: 2.5min rain tips with fill flags, RG01-RG35, 2010-Present, consolidated from tblRG_xx tables in PWDRAIN2010.mdb, 4 columns, including Dtime, Tips, Fill_Flag, and rain_gage.
    • tblModelRain: 15min precipitation, wet weather only, filled, flagged, RG01-RG35
    • fillReport: fill report since 1990, including start and end date time
  • Vieux: Gage-Adjusted Radar Rainfall (GARR) received from Vieux, Inc.
    • RadarRainfall: 15min radar rainfall data by 1x1km2 grid, 2004-present.
    • Radar2sheds: 15min radar rainfall data by each model shed, generated by radar2sheds.py, 2004-present.
  • WPCP: flow/level monitored data for 3 WPCPs and CSPS
    • Logically not belongs to meteorological data, may be set to a separate schema(?)
    • 1min, 5min, hourly, daily, each has different columns and flags
    • SW, SE, NE, CSPS
    • NE_WPCP_hourly, SE_WPCP_hourly, SW_WPCP_hourly : hourly data for the 3 WPCPs
  • ASOS_1min : 1min raw data from ASOS (low priority)
    • 1min_ASOS: 1 min ASOS data from 2002-Present, including visibility, wind, pressure, precipitation, temperature.

  • LOG : keep track of table updates -db_mod_log: tracking sheet that includes 4 columns: dtime, role, table, comment

  • METADATA : data sources, documentations, flags, etc
    • may need a table for flags, so it can be linked by keys
  • REPORTS : paths of monthly meteorological reports (pdf, txt)
    • set up an automated download procedure

Roles

  • admin : super user, all privileges (password: watershed.1)

  • editor : can modify (insert, update, delete) data, but cannot alter table structures (password:readwrite)

  • user : can only read data (no password)

Views

Views are frequently used result set acquired by stored queries. A view is a virtual table computed or collated dynamically from data in the database when access to that view is requested, thus, it takes very little space to store.

Details for views development are in Views_development.

Deployment

  • backend: PostgreSQL DB, hosted on local server or Amazon S3
    • raw data
    • views
    • triggers
    • stored procedure (PL/pgSQL, PL/Python, PL/R)
    • API (via PostgREST)
  • frontend: Shiny app, hosted on local server or Amazon EC2 (firewall/proxy issue)
    • render data inventory stats plots and tables
    • output analysis results (download csv)
    • connect to multipe apps, e.g., big picture, rainfall analysis
  • (?) frontend 2: MS Access DB, connected through ODBC
    • linked tables
    • issue: super slow, key violation
  • analytics: R scripts or shiny apps for dedicated analysis, e.g., 6min -> 15min aggregation
    • the apps are distrubted to local machine, but all access to the same database

Build CentralDB

Start PostgreSQL Server

A configured PostgreSQL v9.6 (x64) installation has been deployed on localhost.

Start the server service: CMD> net start "PostgreSQL 9.6 Server"

system('net start "PostgreSQL 9.6 Server"')

Establish a connection with the database as superuser:

# install.packages('RPostgreSQL')
library(RPostgreSQL)
Loading required package: DBI
# create a connection
# save the password that we can "hide" it as best as we can by collapsing it
pw <- {
  "watershed.1"
}
# Note: if the server is on localhost, no password is required.
# loads the PostgreSQL driver
drv <- dbDriver("PostgreSQL")
# creates a connection to the postgres database
# note that "con" will be used later in each connection to the database
con <- dbConnect(drv,
                 host = "localhost", port = 5433,
                 user = "postgres", password = pw)
rm(pw) # removes the password
# use dbGetQuery() to query
# use dbSendQuery() and fetch() to query in batches
# use dbHasCompleted() to check if the fetch has reach the end

Create Database

Right-click ‘Databases’ -> ‘Create’ -> ‘Database’, specify the database name, etc.

Alternatively, execute the following SQL script:

-- Database: centralDB

-- DROP DATABASE "CentralDB";

CREATE DATABASE "CentralDB"
    WITH
    OWNER = postgres
    ENCODING = 'UTF8'
    LC_COLLATE = 'English_United States.1252'
    LC_CTYPE = 'English_United States.1252'
    TABLESPACE = pg_default
    CONNECTION LIMIT = -1;

COMMENT ON DATABASE "CentralDB" IS 'PHL daily and hourly climatology, hourly precipiation, 6min and hourly tide, PWD rain gauge records, etc. ';

Create Roles

In PgAdmin v4.1, click on the cluster (Hao Zhang’s computer), log in as postgres(password: watershed.1).

Right-click ‘Login/Group Roles’, create the following 3 roles:

  • admin(password: water.123)

  • editor(password: editor)

  • user (no password)

Re-login as admin.

library(RPostgreSQL)
# close previous connection 
# dbDisconnect(con)

# create another connection

# loads the PostgreSQL driver
drv <- dbDriver("PostgreSQL")
# creates a connection to the postgres database
con <- dbConnect(drv, dbname='CentralDB',
                 host = "localhost", port = 5433,
                 user = "admin")

Create Tables & Import Data

The easiest way to create/append data would be utilizing the dbWriteTable function from the RPostgreSQL package. Extracted raw data were formatted as a data frame. The function uses the data type in the source data frame as-is.

Data are coerced to the matched type in the DBMS, any incoercible column is left as TEXT.

QCLCD

Details of NOAA datasets are documented in meteorological data.

QCLCD (https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/orders/qclcd/) contains hourly and daily meteorological data, hourly remarks, and hourly precipitation since 1996-July. Data before 2007-May are compressed as .tar.gz files, and .zip files afterwards. Each compressed file contains a month-worth of data, which were stored in multiple files, where each file contains a type of data, e.g., hourly data, for multiple stations.

To download and extract data from NOAA HTTP server, refer to process_QCLCD.R and process_QCLCD_part2.R.

To format and import data to the database, refer to import_QCLCD.R.

GHCND

GHCND (https://www1.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/data/ghcn/daily/) contains daily meteorological data, including Temperature (Min, Max, Avg), Precipitation, and Snow. To download, format, and import data to the database, refer to process_GHCND.R.

Sample daily_GHCND:

SELECT * FROM "daily_GHCND" WHERE date>'2017-01-01'
ORDER BY date
LIMIT 50

HPCP

HPCP (https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/cdo-web/datasets/PRECIP_HLY/stations/COOP:366889/detail) contains hourly precipitation data for the PHL station from 1900-2013, where dry weather periods were omitted.

To download, format, and import data to the database, refer to process_HPCP.R.

Tide

Tide data are downloaded through NOAA API (http://co-ops.nos.noaa.gov/api/), including 6min and hourly tide observations, and 6min predictions, for multiple NOAA CO-OPS tide stations

To download, format, and import data to the database, refer to process_Tide_1hr.R, process_Tide_6min.R and process_Tide_pred.R.

ASOS 1min data

ASOS 1min data were downloaded to a local directory (../ASOS_1min/), and processed via process_ASOS.R. Raw data were parsed by width, which were determined by manual iteration. A few parse-error exists, e.g., 200312, due to irregular data. All columns were set as TEXT.

Note: time_local is the Local Standard Time (without daylight savings), therefore, it’s always EST (UTC-5).

Sample data:

Radar Rainfall

Radar Rainfall were received from Vieux, Inc. monthly. The datasets are saved at: M:\\Data\\H&H Databases\\RadarRainfall\\Data. Each zip file contains a month of GARR data for each 1x1km2 grid cell, in the format of csv. The datetime is at EST/EDT. There is also a shapefile and a metadata file in the zip file as supplemental information.

Raw data were imported to the radarRainfall table by looping through the zip files, handled by process_radarRainfall.R.

Sample data:

Note: The import was interrrupted because queryign this table is much slower than directly reading the zip file, and storing this table takes a lot of space (4year=10GB), therefore, it is better to leave these files as flat files.

A python program radar2sheds.py is used to convert the radar rainfall from 1x1 km2 cells to model sheds by summing rainfall with the shed areas. A system-wide conversion is taken place manually, and the outputs are saved at: M:\\Models\\raindata\\Radar Rainfall\\forSSOAP.

The post-processed radar rainfall has been extracted from the access database, “RadarRain_TempFlowMon_Sheds_(2004-December2016).accdb”, and imported to the radar2shed table. The process is handled by process_radar2sheds.R.

Sample data:

Since virtual gages are related to the model sheds, when sheds are re-delineated, it will cause inconsistency in data, how to address that possibility?

Grant Privileges

There are multiple scopes of privileges:

Database Privileges

Right-click ‘CentralDB’, click ‘Properties’, go to ‘Security’ tab, set up Grantee-Privileges-Grantor for all three roles. The privileges are for database-level operations, such as ‘CREATE’, ‘TEMPORARY’, ‘CONNECT’.

Table Privileges

Right-click ‘Tables’, click ‘Grant Wizard’, select all tables and follow the wizard to assign table-level privileges, such as ‘SELECT’, ‘INSERT’, ‘UPDATE’, ‘DELETE’,‘TRUNCATE’,‘REFERENCES’,‘TRIGGER’.

Privileges can also be set for an individual table: right-click the table, click ‘Properties’, go to ‘Security’ tab, then specify the Grantee-Privileges-Grantor.

Alternatively, use SQL to set privileges like this:

GRANT ALL ON TABLE "daily_QCLCD" TO admin;

GRANT INSERT, SELECT, UPDATE, DELETE ON TABLE "daily_QCLCD" TO editor;

GRANT SELECT ON TABLE "daily_QCLCD" TO user;

Role Privileges

Right-click the role, click ‘Properties’, go to ‘Privileges’ tab, then toggle the switch for role-level privileges such as ‘can login’, ‘superuser’, ‘create roles’, ‘create database’, ‘update catalog’, ‘inherit rights’, ‘streaming replication’, etc.

Memberships can also be set in the ‘Membership’ tab.

Update database

Most of the update procedures are handled by R scripts, refer to CentralDB Data Updating Procedures for details.

database backup routine

The database is backed-up every 2 weeks, the total backups should not exceeding 3GB (~10 backups), otherwise, older backups are deleted in time order. Any create/delete operation are logged.

The backup is handled by the R script backup_database.R, and a task schedule has been set up, which is exported here.

Alternatively, run the CMD script postgres_Backup.bat, but this script will not delete older backups.

Views (not-implemented yet)

A number of Views are developed for specific analysis, e.g., rainfall for SSOAP, rainfall for SWMM, etc. Details are documented in views_development.

Shiny app development (not-implemented yet)

A shiny app is used as the front-end of the PostgreSQL database, which provides a UI for accessing data and performing several routine analyses. Details are documented in shiny_development.

Clean up

Disconnect from the database:

# close the connection, unload the driver
dbDisconnect(con)
dbUnloadDriver(drv)

Deployment Solutions

  • Plan A: Local DB + shiny app

    Serve the PostgreSQL DB on local server or my personal machine, users/editors uses a shiny app that is hosted by github.com to access/manage data.

    Pros: full accessible, easy to maintain, cost effective

    Cons:

    1. need to install R, shiny and other packages to client machine

    2. DB not accessible outside the proxy

  • Plan B: AWS + shiny server

    Host the PostgrSQL DB and shiny app on AWS.

    Pros: modern MVC, accessible from anywhere, no installation on client machine

    Cons:

    1. editors still need process data locally, then do the database operations with a remote connection through SSH/FTP

    2. AWS can be expensive when the DB grows bigger

    3. DB backup routine needs to be figured out

    4. Public domain, needs authentication

    5. could be slow for sending/receiving large amount of data

  • Plan C: Dedicated Linux Server

    Pros:

    1. works same as the AWS, except instead of uploading to AWS EC2 cloud, payload is now send to a local Linux server.

    2. physically isolated environment, won’t be affected by changes on my local machine

    3. Both Shiny Server and Rstudio Server can be installed on the Linux Server, therefore, no installation is required on client machine

    Cons:

    1. needs a spare computer that can be rebuilt to Linux (Matt used to have a linux machine, is it still available?)

    2. need a fixed IP

    3. not visitable outside the proxy

FAQ

  1. Starting time of the data?

    Everything that is available.

  2. time zone? Daylight savings?

    lst(local standard time), no daylight saving.

  3. QCLCD (hourly data) has version2 and version3, wait for version 3 or download version2 as soon as as it’s available?

    Always use Version3 when it becomes available monthly, unless there is an extreme event that needs to be checked.

  4. 6min or 1hr data for tides?

    Use 6min. Hourly data may miss peaks and troughs. It’s better to have finer grained input data than let SWMM do the interpolation.

    Update: the hourly data were also included in the database as it contains 100 years of historical tide at Pier11.

  5. a separate table for tide prediction?

    yes, tide predictions can be useful for flood risk assessment (prediction) and CSOcast.

  6. how many tide stations?

    • Philadelphia (coast guard)

    • Pier11

    • bridesburg

    • tacony (deprecated in 2014, historical data only)

    • burlington

  7. QCLCD data: data before and after 2007-May have different table structures, save data in two tables or one?

    Pros & Cons 2 tables 1 table
    Pros easy to trace source data easy to query data
    Cons need additional table/view to merge data for analysis lots of NAs and deprecated columns, new data must be reformatted before appending
    Caveat better for archiving data “as-is” better for queries/analyses

    Decision: save as 2 tables, post-process data in R per analysis, e.g., precipitation, snowfall, etc, then output to a shiny frontend UI.

  8. Raw data backup?

    Yes, raw needs to be backed-up in case NOAA changes their data warehouse. For example, QCLCD data is either downloaded as-is (containing data for all stations by month), or as a side product during data processing (containing just one station). I would prefer the first method as it maintains the integrity of source data, even though it consumes more space (~70MB per month). The final decision has not been made yet.

  9. Stored all data as character?

    Data should be converted to its most appropriate type when possible, and timestamps should always converted to EST for insertion.

  10. A ‘cleaned’ table that only include AA report data (always at :54)?

    Yes, this should be one of views.

  11. difference between hourly_precip_QCLCD and hourly_precip_HPCP?

    No difference, refer to QCLCD_HPCP_comp.nb.html

    For comparison between other data sources, refer to LCD_hourly_comp.nb.html.

  12. difference between daily_QCLCD and daily_GHCND?

    No difference, refer to GHCND.nb.html.
